<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
I didn't try the moorlich (didn't feel like making the trip to Lyonesse), but I tried confusing almost every monster in Pennine, including hoary worms, which I'm certain are not linked or baf.  Most of the time, as long as there was something within 250 of it, the monster would go after it and wouldn't even make a move in my direction.  I think what's happening with your tests (especially with the giants) is that there's nothing else for the confused monster to go after besides yourself.  You'll note that with the linked trees, there's another tree that's easily within 250 for the confused monster to go after.<P>However, there were a few times that a monster would make a move towards something near it, then charge me.  When this happened, I did have to move within 250 of another monster to get it off me.  I suspect that this is more prevelant with lower level versions of confuse.  <P>So basicly what you've got is a roll of the dice.  If you're lucky when you first land the spell, the monster will go after something near it (if there's something within 250 anyway), which will then aggro the confused monster.  Obviously, this aggroed monster will always be within 250 of the confused monster, and so there will always be a target besides yourself for the confused monster to go after  (It's important to note that once something attacks the confused monster, it's on the regular aggro list, as well as the ally list.  So if it's you, the confused monster, and one more that's aggroed the confused monster, there is a 55% + 45%/2 or a 77.5% chance that the confused monster will go after the aggroed monster with the level 48 confuse).  Otherwise, it will come after you and will most likely move out of range of its allies, making you the only available target.  Obviously, this limits the usefulness of the spell, and something does need to be done about it.  Of course, this is all based on my observation, which has been horribly wrong before.<P>--------------------<P>Sorcerer-Guinevere
</FONT>
